  "prompt": "Which is the best book for learning python for absolute beginners on their own?",
  "response": "For absolute beginners who are learning Python on their own, **\"Automate the Boring Stuff with Python\" by Al Sweigart** is widely regarded as one of the best books. Here's why it's a great choice:\n\n1. **Beginners-Friendly**: It\u2019s specifically written for beginners with no prior programming experience.  \n2. **Practical Focus**: The book teaches Python by focusing on practical, real-world projects, such as automating repetitive tasks, working with files, web scraping, and more.  \n3. **Engaging Style**: The writing is clear, concise, and easy to follow, making it less intimidating for newcomers.  \n4. **Free Online Resources**: The author provides a free online version of the book and accompanying practice exercises.  \n\nAnother excellent option is **\"Python Crash Course\" by Eric Matthes**, which is also beginner-friendly but includes more structured exercises and projects for hands-on learning.\n\nBoth books are highly recommended, and the choice depends on your learning style:\n- If you like **practical, task-oriented learning**, go with *Automate the Boring Stuff*.  \n- If you prefer a **structured, project-based approach**, choose *Python Crash Course*.  \n\nAdditionally, consider supplementing the book with free online resources like:\n- Python\u2019s official documentation ([https://docs.python.org](https://docs.python.org))  \n- Interactive platforms like [freeCodeCamp](https://www.freecodecamp.org), [Codecademy](https://www.codecademy.com), or [Real Python](https://realpython.com).  \n\nHappy learning! \ud83d\udc0d",
